ype":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anal stretch","Incision and evacuation of haematoma","Prompt haemorrhoidectomy","Pain relief and elective haemorrhoidectomy","Excision and wound debridement"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has two perianal haematoma. These are small collections of blood in the subcutaneous tissues surrounding the anus. They are usually the result of trauma - such as passing a hard stool. These can be treated effectively by \u003Cstrong\u003Eincision and drainage\u003C/strong\u003E, giving the patient prompt relief of her symptoms. This can often be done as a local anaesthetic procedure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA perianal haematoma can easily be mistaken for a prolapsed and thrombosed internal haemorrhoid. In this case, normal anal mucosa can be clearly seen proximal to the haematomas. Thrombosis is a serious complication of internal haemorrhoids. Patients with thrombosed or strangulated haemorrhoids present with severely painful and similar symptoms to that of a perianal haematoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExternal haemorrhoids can present in a similar way to this case, but they arise from immediately distal to the dentate line and would not be so clearly defined as the well circumscribed lesions seen in this photograph.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A painful perianal haematoma can be dealt with expeditiously by simple incision and evacuation.","Perianal haematomas are often caused by straining during bowel movements and can be mistaken for thrombosed haemorrhoids."],"references":["Lohsiriwat V. Treatment of hemorrhoids: A coloproctologist\u0027s view. World J Gastroenterol. 2015 Aug 21;21(31):9245-52. doi: 10.3748/wjg.v21.i31.9245. PMID: 26309351; PMCID: PMC4541377. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26309351/","Lohsiriwat V. Hemorrhoids: from basic pathophysiology to clinical management. World J Gastroenterol. 2012 May 7;18(17):2009-17. 